hands_on_practices.solution:
Adopt the standard thin-lens sign convention: object distances $s$ are positive when the object lies to the left of the lens (incoming light side), and image distances $s'$ are positive when the image lies to the right of the lens. For a thin lens, use the lens equation
$$
\frac{1}{f}=\frac{1}{s}+\frac{1}{s'}.
$$
For lens L1 with focal length $f_{1}=f$ and object distance $s_{1}=3f$, the image distance $s_{1}'$ satisfies
$$
\frac{1}{f}=\frac{1}{3f}+\frac{1}{s_{1}'}
\;\Rightarrow\;
\frac{1}{s_{1}'}=\frac{1}{f}-\frac{1}{3f}=\frac{2}{3f}
\;\Rightarrow\;
s_{1}'=\frac{3f}{2}.
$$
Thus L1 forms a real image at a distance $\frac{3f}{2}$ to its right. The lenses are separated by $6f$, so the distance from this image to L2 is
$$
s_{2}=6f-\frac{3f}{2}=\frac{9f}{2},
$$
which is positive, indicating a real object for L2 located to the left of L2.

For lens L2 with focal length $f_{2}=2f$, the lens equation gives
$$
\frac{1}{2f}=\frac{1}{s_{2}}+\frac{1}{s_{2}'}
\;\Rightarrow\;
\frac{1}{s_{2}'}=\frac{1}{2f}-\frac{1}{s_{2}}=\frac{1}{2f}-\frac{2}{9f}=\frac{5}{18f}
\;\Rightarrow\;
s_{2}'=\frac{18f}{5}.
$$
Since $s_{2}'>0$, the final image is located to the right of L2 at a distance $\frac{18f}{5}$ from L2. This satisfies the requested sign convention.
